{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014Ly7gdkN3pM2SNaecquFX4","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have enough detail to write a thorough review. Here is the analysis:\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: title-extractor.ts (Changes A-F)\n\n## Review Metrics\n- Files Reviewed: 1\n- Critical Issues: 0\n- High Priority: 2\n- Medium Priority: 3\n- Suggestions: 3\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThe six changes are mechanically sound and the logic flows correctly in all cases. The two most significant issues are: a subtle duplication between `applyBlindOcrRepair` and `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` that creates a maintenance trap (the ALL_CAPS path in the outer function has intentionally different behaviour, but the two are easy to confuse), and a threshold in `hasErraticCasing` that fires too eagerly on short legitimate title words, which could cause quiet regressions.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority\n\n### 1. `applyBlindOcrRepair` ALL_CAPS branch silently diverges from `applyBlindOcrRepairToken`\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:913-926`\n\n**Impact**: The outer function's ALL_CAPS path (lines 913-926) applies `¡→I`, `€→E`, and `[ÍÌ]→I` repairs that the inner function's ALL_CAPS path (lines 879-887) does not. The inner function is reached when individual tokens inside a mixed-case string happen to be ALL_CAPS. Those three repairs are silently skipped for such tokens, which means a mixed-case line like `\"Soup ÍZ READY\"` loses the `Í→I` fix that a fully-uppercased line would get.\n\nWhether that's intentional or an oversight is unclear from the code. If it's intentional, a comment is needed. If it's an oversight, the repairs need to be added to the token-level path.\n\n**Root Cause**: When Change A extended `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` for 0/4/5 it correctly mirrored the outer function. But the `¡/€/ÍÌ` repairs in the outer function were never carried down, and there is no comment explaining why.\n\n**Solution**: Either add the three repairs to `applyBlindOcrRepairToken`'s ALL_CAPS branch, or add an explicit comment:\n\n```typescript\nfunction applyBlindOcrRepairToken(token: string, oneLetter: \"i\" | \"l\"): string {\n  if (isAllCaps(token) && token.length > 1) {\n    return token\n      .replace(/1/g, \"I\")\n      .replace(/0(?=[A-ZÀ-Ż])/g, \"O\")\n      .replace(/(?<=[A-ZÀ-Ż])0/g, \"O\")\n      .replace(/4(?=[A-ZÀ-Ż])/g, \"A\")\n      .replace(/(?<=[A-ZÀ-Ż])4/g, \"A\")\n      .replace(/5(?=[A-ZÀ-Ż])/g, \"S\")\n      .replace(/(?<=[A-ZÀ-Ż])5/g, \"S\")\n      // Keep in sync with applyBlindOcrRepair's ALL_CAPS branch\n      .replace(/¡/g, \"I\")\n      .replace(/€/g, \"E\")\n      .replace(/[ÍÌ]/g, \"I\");\n  }\n  // ...\n}\n```\n\nOr, if the divergence is intentional (e.g. mixed-case ÍÌ repairs are unwanted), add:\n\n```typescript\n// Note: ¡/€/ÍÌ repairs intentionally omitted here; they only apply when the\n// whole string is ALL_CAPS (handled in applyBlindOcrRepair). Per-token ALL_CAPS\n// detection inside mixed-case strings is a weaker signal.\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. `hasErraticCasing` threshold fires on 3-letter title-case tokens\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:930-939`\n\n**Impact**: The condition `upperInner >= 2 && upperInner >= lowerInner * 0.3` fires when `inner` (everything after the first character) has 2 upper-case letters regardless of the total length. For a 4-character token like `\"ZaLe\"`, `inner = \"aLe\"`, `upperInner = 1`, `lowerInner = 2` — that's safe. But a 4-character token like `\"ZALe\"`, `inner = \"ALe\"`, `upperInner = 2`, `lowerInner = 1` — fires. `0.3 * 1 = 0.3 ≤ 2`, so the 0.3 ratio guard is essentially inert on very short tokens.\n\nReal-world consequence: a recipe title containing a legitimate abbreviation or acronym inside a longer candidate (e.g. `\"Zupa z ZA\")`) — more importantly, this path feeds `normalizeErraticCasing`, which lowercases the `slice(1)` of the token. A false-positive here silently mutates the candidate text before scoring, which is harder to debug than a filter rejection.\n\n**Root Cause**: The `>= 2` absolute count was chosen to exclude 1-upper noise but was not paired with a minimum token length beyond the existing `< 3` guard.\n\n**Solution**: Raise the minimum token length before the ratio check applies, or require `upperInner` to be a larger fraction of total inner length:\n\n```typescript\nfunction hasErraticCasing(text: string): boolean {\n  return text.split(/\\s+/).some(word => {\n    if (word.length < 5) return false;          // ← was < 3; 4-char tokens are too short to judge\n    if (isAllCaps(word)) return false;\n    const inner = word.slice(1);\n    const upperInner = (inner.match(/[A-ZÀ-Ż]/g) || []).length;\n    const lowerInner = (inner.match(/[a-zà-ż]/g) || []).length;\n    // At least 2 internal caps AND they make up ≥30% of inner letters\n    return upperInner >= 2 && lowerInner > 0 && upperInner / (upperInner + lowerInner) >= 0.3;\n  });\n}\n```\n\nThe division form `upperInner / (upperInner + lowerInner)` is more stable than `upperInner >= lowerInner * 0.3` because it is not skewed when `lowerInner` is 0 or 1. The current form allows `upperInner = 2, lowerInner = 0` (`\"ZAA\"`) to pass: `0 * 0.3 = 0 ≤ 2`, so a purely upper-inner token that isn't caught by `isAllCaps` (possible when the first char is lowercase) can trigger normalization.\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority\n\n### 3. `passesHardFilters`: OCR normalization after `isLikelyGarbled` may produce a false filter-pass\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:401-415`\n\n**Impact**: The check order is: `isLikelyGarbled(text)` → (reject) → `looksLikeCookingInstruction(text)` → `looksLikeCookingInstruction(ocrNormForInstruction)`. The ordering is correct for the stated goal. However, `ocrNormForInstruction` is computed unconditionally even when `isLikelyGarbled` would have returned early, which is harmless but slightly wasteful. More importantly: the OCR norm only applies `4→a` in lowercase context. If the original text already passed `isLikelyGarbled`, then the 4 inside it is lowercase-adjacent (otherwise it would look like ALL_CAPS digit noise, not OCR artifact). This is internally consistent.\n\nThe logic ordering issue raised in the prompt (\"is the ordering correct?\") is actually fine: `looksLikeCookingInstruction(text)` runs first on the raw text, and only if that passes does the normalized version get checked. There is no case where running the normalized version first would produce a different filter outcome, because the normalized version is strictly more permissive at matching cooking instructions (it fixes OCR corruptions that would prevent a match). Running the raw check first is a micro-optimization — it avoids the regex overhead when the raw text already matches.\n\n**Minor issue**: `ocrNormForInstruction` is computed before it is known whether the early guards (lines 402-406) will return. Move its initialization after line 406 to make the data-flow intent clearer and avoid building a string that may never be used:\n\n```typescript\nfunction passesHardFilters(text: string): boolean {\n  if (text.length < 3 || text.length > 80) return false;\n  if (looksLikeIngredient(text)) return false;\n  if (startsWithNumber(text)) return false;\n  if (looksLikeMetadata(text)) return false;\n  if (isLikelyGarbled(text)) return false;\n  if (looksLikeCookingInstruction(text)) return false;\n  // Compute OCR norm only when needed\n  const ocrNormForInstruction = text\n    .replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])4/g, \"a\")\n    .replace(/4(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, \"a\");\n  if (ocrNormForInstruction !== text && looksLikeCookingInstruction(ocrNormForInstruction)) return false;\n  // ...\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 4. `isLikelyGarbled` multi-word camel-case check has a gap for exactly 2-char words\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:340-349`\n\n**Impact**: The new `hasGarbledCamelCase` check (Change B) requires `w.length >= 3`. A 2-character garbled token like `\"aB\"` inside a multi-word candidate would be missed by this branch. It would also be missed by `hasGarbledWord` (which requires `w.replace(/[^a-z]/g, \"\").length <= 2` but also `^[a-z]` start, so `\"aB\"` does match `hasGarbledWord`). Actually tracing through: `\"aB\"` starts with lowercase, has 1 lowercase-only char (length 1 after stripping non-lowercase), which is `<= 2`, and is presumably not in `commonShort2`. So `hasGarbledWord` would catch it. The gap between the two checks is zero for tokens starting with a lowercase letter.\n\nHowever, a token like `\"Ab\"` (uppercase start, 2 chars) with lowercase→uppercase transition would not be caught: `hasGarbledWord` requires `^[a-z]` (fails), and `hasGarbledCamelCase` requires `length >= 3` (fails). This is probably fine since `\"Ab\"` is a plausible abbreviation, but worth noting it is a deliberate blind spot.\n\nNo code change needed — this documents expected behaviour.\n\n---\n\n### 5. `stripTrailingPageRef` regex does not anchor against mid-string matches\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:556-558`\n\n**Impact**: The regex `\\s*\\((?:p\\.?\\s*)?\\d{1,4}\\)\\s*$` is end-anchored (`$`) and is correct. However the `.trim()` call after the replacement means a title like `\"Cake (serves 4)\"` would not be affected (the inner group is not `p.` prefixed and the digit is followed by `)`, but the full match is `(4)` — wait, `\"(serves 4)\"` does not match because `serves` precedes the digit). The regex correctly only matches `(N)` and `(p. N)` forms. No issue here.\n\nOne edge case: `\"RECIPE NAME (p.42)\"` (no space after `p.`) — the pattern `p\\.?\\s*` allows `p.` followed by zero spaces, so this matches. `\"RECIPE NAME (p42)\"` (no dot) also matches because `\\.?` makes the dot optional. Whether stripping `(p42)` is desired is a question of how common that OCR artifact is; it seems acceptable.\n\n---\n\n## LOW Priority (Opportunities)\n\n### 6. `normalizeErraticCasing` calls `hasErraticCasing` per-token, which itself iterates words\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:941-950`\n\n`normalizeErraticCasing` splits on whitespace-preserving groups (`/(\\s+)/`) and calls `hasErraticCasing(token)` on each non-whitespace piece. `hasErraticCasing` then calls `text.split(/\\s+/).some(...)` on each token — but since `token` is already a single word (no spaces), `.split(/\\s+/)` returns a one-element array. This is correct but does redundant tokenization. Not performance-critical at this scale but slightly confusing to read.\n\n### 7. `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` has an inconsistency in diacritic coverage\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:362`\n\nThe new Change C verbs include `ugotowa[cć]` and `obtoczy[cć]` and `podawa[cć]` — good, these cover OCR corruption of the final ć. But `upiecz` has no variant for `upieci` or other OCR corruptions. This is minor and consistent with the comment \"OCR-resilient forms\" being selectively applied where observed.\n\n### 8. The `hasPipePreamble` variable scope could mislead future readers\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1165`\n\n`hasPipePreamble` is declared at the outer scope but only set inside the `allPrecedingFiltered` block (lines 1178-1187). A reader scanning from the cap logic (line 1231) upward sees a `let` that appears settable anywhere but is only set in one guarded branch. The comment on line 1229 (\"hasPipePreamble is set above inside the allPrecedingFiltered block, so it is only true when the preamble-bonus logic also fired\") is accurate but could be enforced structurally by initializing it inside the `if (allPrecedingFiltered)` block:\n\n```typescript\nlet hasPipePreamble = false;\nif (allPrecedingFiltered) {\n  let hasStructuralPreamble = false;\n  // ...set hasPipePreamble here...\n}\n```\n\nThis is already the case — `hasPipePreamble` starts `false` and the only assignment is inside `allPrecedingFiltered`. No change needed, but worth noting the comment is doing necessary work.\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The letter-adjacent guard pattern (`(?<=[a-zà-ż])4` + `4(?=[a-zà-ż])`) is used consistently for all digit→letter substitutions across both branches of `applyBlindOcrRepairToken`. Change A applied it correctly to the new 0/4/5 cases.\n- The `hasPipePreamble` flag correctly gates the higher `maxPositionalBoost` only when both conditions (pipe preamble AND all-preceding-filtered) were satisfied. This is tighter than a simple `isAllCaps` check would be.\n- The `looksLikeCookingInstruction` minimum word count guard (`words.length < 4`) is a good pre-filter that prevents both the English and Polish regexes from being run on short candidates.\n- `stripTrailingPageRef` is correctly applied in the pipeline before `repairOcrText`, so the stripped result feeds into OCR repair cleanly without a stray digit confusing the 0/4/5 substitutions.\n\n## Systemic Patterns\n\nThe codebase applies OCR normalization in at least three places for distinct purposes: `applyBlindOcrRepair` (general repair before scoring), `ocrNormForInstruction` (targeted repair before filter check), and the erratic-casing normalization. These three mechanisms overlap in coverage but serve different pipeline stages. As more OCR repair cases are added (Change A is the third expansion of the 0/4/5 substitutions), there is a growing risk that a repair added to one path is missed in another. A shared `OCR_DIGIT_SUBSTITUTIONS` constant mapping digit→letter pairs with their guard contexts would make cross-path consistency auditable at a glance and would have prevented the `¡/€/ÍÌ` divergence noted in issue 1."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a3a4e48af52f2f061 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 25151\ntool_uses: 9\nduration_ms: 106423</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f3952b68-8982-4bda-aefc-f210110437d7","uuid":"dd4cec34-b623-46d8-a48a-9d26fc52bc28","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Review code quality and correctness of the uncommitted changes in lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts.\n\nThis is a title extraction module for recipe photos in a React Native/Expo app. The changes implement an improvement plan with 6 changes (A-F). Here's a summary of the uncommitted diff:\n\n**Change A**: Extended `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` to handle 0→o, 4→a, 5→s in mixed-case context (with letter-adjacent guards). Previously only handled 1→i/l, ¡→i, €→e.\n\n**Change B**: Added multi-word garbled token detection in `isLikelyGarbled` - now checks individual words within multi-word candidates for lowercase→uppercase transitions (capped at length 7, Mc/Mac exempt). Also added Mc/Mac exemption to the existing single-word check.\n\n**Change C**: Expanded `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` regex with new verbs: ugotuj, ugotowac, upiecz, podawac, zapiekaj, obtocz, obtoczyc, podgrzej, podgrzewaj.\n\n**Change D**: Added OCR normalization (4→a) before cooking instruction check in `passesHardFilters`. Creates `ocrNormForInstruction` string, checks it against `looksLikeCookingInstruction` if different from original.\n\n**Change E**: Raised `maxPositionalBoost` cap from 0.15 to 0.18 for pipe-metadata + ALL_CAPS candidates. Tracks `hasPipePreamble` flag, refactored preamble detection from `.some()` to a for-loop.\n\n**Change F**: Added `stripTrailingPageRef` function to strip trailing `(N)` or `(p. N)` patterns. Applied in `buildCandidates` pipeline.\n\n**Other changes in the committed iteration 28 (already in HEAD)**:\n- Unified instruction+prose prologue skipping in `findBurstEnd`\n- Expanded overflow markers\n- `isTitleAbsentPage` now takes a `startFrom` parameter\n- `buildCandidates` now generates multiple OCR variants and handles erratic casing\n- `hasErraticCasing` / `normalizeErraticCasing` functions added\n- `burstEnd` default changed from 0 to `lines.length`\n- Direct-successor bonus now scans backward past blank lines\n\nFocus on:\n1. **Correctness**: Are the regex patterns correct? Are there edge cases that could cause false positives/negatives?\n2. **Code duplication**: The ALL_CAPS branch in `applyBlindOcrRepair` (line 913-926) now duplicates the logic in `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` (line 878-887). Is this a problem?\n3. **Logic bugs**: In `passesHardFilters`, the original `looksLikeCookingInstruction(text)` check runs before the OCR-normalized version. Is the ordering correct?\n4. **Naming**: Are function and variable names clear?\n5. **The `hasErraticCasing` threshold**: `upperInner >= 2 && upperInner >= lowerInner * 0.3` - is this robust?\n\nRead the actual file at /Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts to verify my summary. Check lines 878-928 (OCR repair), 295-352 (garbled detection), 355-415 (cooking instructions + hard filters), 930-950 (erratic casing), 1160-1240 (positional bonuses).","agentId":"a3a4e48af52f2f061","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have enough detail to write a thorough review. Here is the analysis:\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: title-extractor.ts (Changes A-F)\n\n## Review Metrics\n- Files Reviewed: 1\n- Critical Issues: 0\n- High Priority: 2\n- Medium Priority: 3\n- Suggestions: 3\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThe six changes are mechanically sound and the logic flows correctly in all cases. The two most significant issues are: a subtle duplication between `applyBlindOcrRepair` and `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` that creates a maintenance trap (the ALL_CAPS path in the outer function has intentionally different behaviour, but the two are easy to confuse), and a threshold in `hasErraticCasing` that fires too eagerly on short legitimate title words, which could cause quiet regressions.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority\n\n### 1. `applyBlindOcrRepair` ALL_CAPS branch silently diverges from `applyBlindOcrRepairToken`\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:913-926`\n\n**Impact**: The outer function's ALL_CAPS path (lines 913-926) applies `¡→I`, `€→E`, and `[ÍÌ]→I` repairs that the inner function's ALL_CAPS path (lines 879-887) does not. The inner function is reached when individual tokens inside a mixed-case string happen to be ALL_CAPS. Those three repairs are silently skipped for such tokens, which means a mixed-case line like `\"Soup ÍZ READY\"` loses the `Í→I` fix that a fully-uppercased line would get.\n\nWhether that's intentional or an oversight is unclear from the code. If it's intentional, a comment is needed. If it's an oversight, the repairs need to be added to the token-level path.\n\n**Root Cause**: When Change A extended `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` for 0/4/5 it correctly mirrored the outer function. But the `¡/€/ÍÌ` repairs in the outer function were never carried down, and there is no comment explaining why.\n\n**Solution**: Either add the three repairs to `applyBlindOcrRepairToken`'s ALL_CAPS branch, or add an explicit comment:\n\n```typescript\nfunction applyBlindOcrRepairToken(token: string, oneLetter: \"i\" | \"l\"): string {\n  if (isAllCaps(token) && token.length > 1) {\n    return token\n      .replace(/1/g, \"I\")\n      .replace(/0(?=[A-ZÀ-Ż])/g, \"O\")\n      .replace(/(?<=[A-ZÀ-Ż])0/g, \"O\")\n      .replace(/4(?=[A-ZÀ-Ż])/g, \"A\")\n      .replace(/(?<=[A-ZÀ-Ż])4/g, \"A\")\n      .replace(/5(?=[A-ZÀ-Ż])/g, \"S\")\n      .replace(/(?<=[A-ZÀ-Ż])5/g, \"S\")\n      // Keep in sync with applyBlindOcrRepair's ALL_CAPS branch\n      .replace(/¡/g, \"I\")\n      .replace(/€/g, \"E\")\n      .replace(/[ÍÌ]/g, \"I\");\n  }\n  // ...\n}\n```\n\nOr, if the divergence is intentional (e.g. mixed-case ÍÌ repairs are unwanted), add:\n\n```typescript\n// Note: ¡/€/ÍÌ repairs intentionally omitted here; they only apply when the\n// whole string is ALL_CAPS (handled in applyBlindOcrRepair). Per-token ALL_CAPS\n// detection inside mixed-case strings is a weaker signal.\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. `hasErraticCasing` threshold fires on 3-letter title-case tokens\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:930-939`\n\n**Impact**: The condition `upperInner >= 2 && upperInner >= lowerInner * 0.3` fires when `inner` (everything after the first character) has 2 upper-case letters regardless of the total length. For a 4-character token like `\"ZaLe\"`, `inner = \"aLe\"`, `upperInner = 1`, `lowerInner = 2` — that's safe. But a 4-character token like `\"ZALe\"`, `inner = \"ALe\"`, `upperInner = 2`, `lowerInner = 1` — fires. `0.3 * 1 = 0.3 ≤ 2`, so the 0.3 ratio guard is essentially inert on very short tokens.\n\nReal-world consequence: a recipe title containing a legitimate abbreviation or acronym inside a longer candidate (e.g. `\"Zupa z ZA\")`) — more importantly, this path feeds `normalizeErraticCasing`, which lowercases the `slice(1)` of the token. A false-positive here silently mutates the candidate text before scoring, which is harder to debug than a filter rejection.\n\n**Root Cause**: The `>= 2` absolute count was chosen to exclude 1-upper noise but was not paired with a minimum token length beyond the existing `< 3` guard.\n\n**Solution**: Raise the minimum token length before the ratio check applies, or require `upperInner` to be a larger fraction of total inner length:\n\n```typescript\nfunction hasErraticCasing(text: string): boolean {\n  return text.split(/\\s+/).some(word => {\n    if (word.length < 5) return false;          // ← was < 3; 4-char tokens are too short to judge\n    if (isAllCaps(word)) return false;\n    const inner = word.slice(1);\n    const upperInner = (inner.match(/[A-ZÀ-Ż]/g) || []).length;\n    const lowerInner = (inner.match(/[a-zà-ż]/g) || []).length;\n    // At least 2 internal caps AND they make up ≥30% of inner letters\n    return upperInner >= 2 && lowerInner > 0 && upperInner / (upperInner + lowerInner) >= 0.3;\n  });\n}\n```\n\nThe division form `upperInner / (upperInner + lowerInner)` is more stable than `upperInner >= lowerInner * 0.3` because it is not skewed when `lowerInner` is 0 or 1. The current form allows `upperInner = 2, lowerInner = 0` (`\"ZAA\"`) to pass: `0 * 0.3 = 0 ≤ 2`, so a purely upper-inner token that isn't caught by `isAllCaps` (possible when the first char is lowercase) can trigger normalization.\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority\n\n### 3. `passesHardFilters`: OCR normalization after `isLikelyGarbled` may produce a false filter-pass\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:401-415`\n\n**Impact**: The check order is: `isLikelyGarbled(text)` → (reject) → `looksLikeCookingInstruction(text)` → `looksLikeCookingInstruction(ocrNormForInstruction)`. The ordering is correct for the stated goal. However, `ocrNormForInstruction` is computed unconditionally even when `isLikelyGarbled` would have returned early, which is harmless but slightly wasteful. More importantly: the OCR norm only applies `4→a` in lowercase context. If the original text already passed `isLikelyGarbled`, then the 4 inside it is lowercase-adjacent (otherwise it would look like ALL_CAPS digit noise, not OCR artifact). This is internally consistent.\n\nThe logic ordering issue raised in the prompt (\"is the ordering correct?\") is actually fine: `looksLikeCookingInstruction(text)` runs first on the raw text, and only if that passes does the normalized version get checked. There is no case where running the normalized version first would produce a different filter outcome, because the normalized version is strictly more permissive at matching cooking instructions (it fixes OCR corruptions that would prevent a match). Running the raw check first is a micro-optimization — it avoids the regex overhead when the raw text already matches.\n\n**Minor issue**: `ocrNormForInstruction` is computed before it is known whether the early guards (lines 402-406) will return. Move its initialization after line 406 to make the data-flow intent clearer and avoid building a string that may never be used:\n\n```typescript\nfunction passesHardFilters(text: string): boolean {\n  if (text.length < 3 || text.length > 80) return false;\n  if (looksLikeIngredient(text)) return false;\n  if (startsWithNumber(text)) return false;\n  if (looksLikeMetadata(text)) return false;\n  if (isLikelyGarbled(text)) return false;\n  if (looksLikeCookingInstruction(text)) return false;\n  // Compute OCR norm only when needed\n  const ocrNormForInstruction = text\n    .replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])4/g, \"a\")\n    .replace(/4(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, \"a\");\n  if (ocrNormForInstruction !== text && looksLikeCookingInstruction(ocrNormForInstruction)) return false;\n  // ...\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 4. `isLikelyGarbled` multi-word camel-case check has a gap for exactly 2-char words\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:340-349`\n\n**Impact**: The new `hasGarbledCamelCase` check (Change B) requires `w.length >= 3`. A 2-character garbled token like `\"aB\"` inside a multi-word candidate would be missed by this branch. It would also be missed by `hasGarbledWord` (which requires `w.replace(/[^a-z]/g, \"\").length <= 2` but also `^[a-z]` start, so `\"aB\"` does match `hasGarbledWord`). Actually tracing through: `\"aB\"` starts with lowercase, has 1 lowercase-only char (length 1 after stripping non-lowercase), which is `<= 2`, and is presumably not in `commonShort2`. So `hasGarbledWord` would catch it. The gap between the two checks is zero for tokens starting with a lowercase letter.\n\nHowever, a token like `\"Ab\"` (uppercase start, 2 chars) with lowercase→uppercase transition would not be caught: `hasGarbledWord` requires `^[a-z]` (fails), and `hasGarbledCamelCase` requires `length >= 3` (fails). This is probably fine since `\"Ab\"` is a plausible abbreviation, but worth noting it is a deliberate blind spot.\n\nNo code change needed — this documents expected behaviour.\n\n---\n\n### 5. `stripTrailingPageRef` regex does not anchor against mid-string matches\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:556-558`\n\n**Impact**: The regex `\\s*\\((?:p\\.?\\s*)?\\d{1,4}\\)\\s*$` is end-anchored (`$`) and is correct. However the `.trim()` call after the replacement means a title like `\"Cake (serves 4)\"` would not be affected (the inner group is not `p.` prefixed and the digit is followed by `)`, but the full match is `(4)` — wait, `\"(serves 4)\"` does not match because `serves` precedes the digit). The regex correctly only matches `(N)` and `(p. N)` forms. No issue here.\n\nOne edge case: `\"RECIPE NAME (p.42)\"` (no space after `p.`) — the pattern `p\\.?\\s*` allows `p.` followed by zero spaces, so this matches. `\"RECIPE NAME (p42)\"` (no dot) also matches because `\\.?` makes the dot optional. Whether stripping `(p42)` is desired is a question of how common that OCR artifact is; it seems acceptable.\n\n---\n\n## LOW Priority (Opportunities)\n\n### 6. `normalizeErraticCasing` calls `hasErraticCasing` per-token, which itself iterates words\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:941-950`\n\n`normalizeErraticCasing` splits on whitespace-preserving groups (`/(\\s+)/`) and calls `hasErraticCasing(token)` on each non-whitespace piece. `hasErraticCasing` then calls `text.split(/\\s+/).some(...)` on each token — but since `token` is already a single word (no spaces), `.split(/\\s+/)` returns a one-element array. This is correct but does redundant tokenization. Not performance-critical at this scale but slightly confusing to read.\n\n### 7. `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` has an inconsistency in diacritic coverage\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:362`\n\nThe new Change C verbs include `ugotowa[cć]` and `obtoczy[cć]` and `podawa[cć]` — good, these cover OCR corruption of the final ć. But `upiecz` has no variant for `upieci` or other OCR corruptions. This is minor and consistent with the comment \"OCR-resilient forms\" being selectively applied where observed.\n\n### 8. The `hasPipePreamble` variable scope could mislead future readers\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1165`\n\n`hasPipePreamble` is declared at the outer scope but only set inside the `allPrecedingFiltered` block (lines 1178-1187). A reader scanning from the cap logic (line 1231) upward sees a `let` that appears settable anywhere but is only set in one guarded branch. The comment on line 1229 (\"hasPipePreamble is set above inside the allPrecedingFiltered block, so it is only true when the preamble-bonus logic also fired\") is accurate but could be enforced structurally by initializing it inside the `if (allPrecedingFiltered)` block:\n\n```typescript\nlet hasPipePreamble = false;\nif (allPrecedingFiltered) {\n  let hasStructuralPreamble = false;\n  // ...set hasPipePreamble here...\n}\n```\n\nThis is already the case — `hasPipePreamble` starts `false` and the only assignment is inside `allPrecedingFiltered`. No change needed, but worth noting the comment is doing necessary work.\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The letter-adjacent guard pattern (`(?<=[a-zà-ż])4` + `4(?=[a-zà-ż])`) is used consistently for all digit→letter substitutions across both branches of `applyBlindOcrRepairToken`. Change A applied it correctly to the new 0/4/5 cases.\n- The `hasPipePreamble` flag correctly gates the higher `maxPositionalBoost` only when both conditions (pipe preamble AND all-preceding-filtered) were satisfied. This is tighter than a simple `isAllCaps` check would be.\n- The `looksLikeCookingInstruction` minimum word count guard (`words.length < 4`) is a good pre-filter that prevents both the English and Polish regexes from being run on short candidates.\n- `stripTrailingPageRef` is correctly applied in the pipeline before `repairOcrText`, so the stripped result feeds into OCR repair cleanly without a stray digit confusing the 0/4/5 substitutions.\n\n## Systemic Patterns\n\nThe codebase applies OCR normalization in at least three places for distinct purposes: `applyBlindOcrRepair` (general repair before scoring), `ocrNormForInstruction` (targeted repair before filter check), and the erratic-casing normalization. These three mechanisms overlap in coverage but serve different pipeline stages. As more OCR repair cases are added (Change A is the third expansion of the 0/4/5 substitutions), there is a growing risk that a repair added to one path is missed in another. A shared `OCR_DIGIT_SUBSTITUTIONS` constant mapping digit→letter pairs with their guard contexts would make cross-path consistency auditable at a glance and would have prevented the `¡/€/ÍÌ` divergence noted in issue 1."}],"totalDurationMs":106423,"totalTokens":25151,"totalToolUseCount":9,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":956,"cache_read_input_tokens":19974,"output_tokens":4220,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":956},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
