after the existing `¡→i` and `€→e` substitutions), with the identical lookaround pattern `[a-zà-ż]`. This matches the plan precisely.\n\nThe plan also noted no dual-variant is needed for `0` because `S01e` now resolves in a single pass. The `generateBlindOcrVariants` function (lines 958–976) is unchanged — it still only produces `i`-variant and `l`-variant based on the `1` ambiguity, which is correct: `0→o`, `4→a`, `5→s` are all unambiguous and do not require dual-variant handling.\n\n---\n\n## Change B — Garbled multi-word detection\n\n**Verdict: DEVIATION from plan — added a `length <= 7` cap. This is a well-justified improvement.**\n\nThe plan specified:\n```typescript\nw.length >= 3 &&\n/[a-z][A-Z]/.test(w) &&\n!/^(Mc|Mac)[A-Z]/.test(w)\n```\n\nThe implementation at lines 340–346 adds `w.length <= 7`:\n```typescript\nw.length >= 3 &&\nw.length <= 7 &&\n/[a-z][A-Z]/.test(w) &&\n!/^(Mc|Mac)[A-Z]/.test(w)\n```\n\nThe inline comment explains the rationale: OCR dropped-space artifacts like `\"withGarlic\"` (10 chars) contain a camelCase transition but are not garbled — they are two legitimately fused words. True garbled tokens (`XxYyZz`, `UuIw`) are short. The cap prevents false positives on real compound-word OCR artifacts that happen to have a case transition.\n\nThis is a sensible, conservative tightening that reduces the risk of over-rejection. The plan's open question 3 noted awareness of the false-positive risk from the `4→a` guard; the same pragmatic spirit applies here.\n\nOne minor concern: the upper bound of 7 is not derived from any documented evidence. The comment cites `\"withGarlic\"` at 10 chars as the motivating example, which leaves a gap between 7 and 10. A compound like `\"withOil\"` (7 chars) would still be caught. This boundary deserves a note in the iteration docs if it produces a regression, but it is not a correctness bug.\n\n---\n\n## Change C — Polish cooking verb filter\n\n**Verdict: CORRECT, all plan verbs present — with one clarification.**\n\nThe plan listed these additions:\n- `ugotuj` — present\n- `ugotowac` — present as `ugotowa[cć]`\n- `upiecz` — present\n- `usmaz` — note: `usma[zż]` was already in the regex; not a new addition\n- `podawa[cć]` — present as `podawa[cć]`\n- `zapiekaj` — present\n- `obtocz` — present\n- `obtoczyc` — present as `obtoczy[cć]`\n- `podgrzej` — present\n- `podgrzewaj` — present\n\nAll plan-specified verbs are accounted for in the regex at line 362. The diacritic-tolerant forms (e.g., `ugotowa[cć]`, `obtoczy[cć]`) are correct OCR-resilient variants.\n\nOne observation: the plan also said \"add an OCR-aware variant to the regex or by normalizing `4→a` before the instruction check\" for `Podaw4ć`. The implementation chose normalization (Change D) rather than a regex variant for that specific case, which is appropriate — see Change D below.\n\n---\n\n## Change D — OCR normalization for instruction detection\n\n**Verdict: GOOD SIMPLIFICATION relative to the plan, with one meaningful omission.**\n\nThe plan proposed a case-aware `4→a` normalization using a callback:\n```typescript\nconst ocrNormalized = text\n  .replace(/4(?=[a-zà-żA-ZÀ-Ż])/g, (_, offset) =>\n    /[A-ZÀ-Ż]/.test(text[offset]) ? \"A\" : \"a\")\n  .replace(/(?<=[a-zà-żA-ZÀ-Ż])4/g, (_, offset) =>\n    /[A-ZÀ-Ż]/.test(text[offset - 1]) ? \"A\" : \"a\");\n```\n\nThe implementation at lines 411–413 uses the simpler form:\n```typescript\nconst ocrNormForInstruction = text\n  .replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])4/g, \"a\")\n  .replace(/4(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, \"a\");\n```\n\nThis simplification is justified: the purpose is only to detect cooking instructions (not to produce a clean output string), and the instruction regex is case-insensitive (`/i` flag). Replacing `4` with lowercase `\"a\"` is sufficient for matching `Podawać` regardless of the capital `P`. The plan's case-preserving callback was over-engineered for this use case.\n\nThe meaningful omission: the plan specified normalizing `4→a` when adjacent to uppercase OR lowercase letters (using `[a-zà-żA-ZÀ-Ż]`), while the implementation only guards for adjacent lowercase (`[a-zà-ż]`). The concrete failure case is `\"Podaw4ć\"` — the `4` is between lowercase `w` and lowercase `ć`, so the lowercase guard fires and this case is handled correctly. However, if an ALL_CAPS cooking instruction like `\"PODAW4Ć\"` appeared, the lowercase guard would not fire. Given that cooking instruction detection already uses a case-insensitive regex, the practical impact is zero for the targeted pattern — but this is a narrower guard than the plan specified.\n\nThe plan also said \"It should use the same substitution logic as `applyBlindOcrRepairToken`\" to avoid divergence. The implementation uses only the downstream (lookahead) form `.replace(/4(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, \"a\")` and the lookbehind form, which matches `applyBlindOcrRepairToken`'s mixed-case logic. This cross-iteration constraint is respected.\n\n**One logical issue in the implementation** (medium priority): at line 414, `looksLikeCookingInstruction(text)` is called on the original (un-normalized) text, then at line 415 on the normalized form. The `if (looksLikeCookingInstruction(text)) return false;` at line 414 is redundant — it duplicates the check that already existed at line 414 before this change, which is fine. But the normalized check at line 415 is only run when `ocrNormForInstruction !== text` (the normalization changed something). This gating is correct and intentional: it avoids an extra function call when no `4` adjacent to lowercase is present.\n\n---\n\n## Change E — Positional bonus cap\n\n**Verdict: CORRECT, exactly matches plan.**\n\nThe plan specified:\n```typescript\nconst maxPositionalBoost =\n  hasPipeSeparatedMetadataPreamble && isAllCaps ? 0.18 : 0.15;\n```\n\nThe implementation at lines 1231–1232:\n```typescript\nconst maxPositionalBoost =\n  hasPipePreamble && isAllCaps(firstCandidate.text) ? 0.18 : 0.15;\n```\n\nVariable name `hasPipePreamble` vs `hasPipeSeparatedMetadataPreamble` in the plan — this is the same concept. The plan says \"when the candidate has pipe-separated metadata on the preceding line AND the candidate is ALL_CAPS.\" The implementation guards `hasPipePreamble` correctly: it is only set to `true` inside the `allPrecedingFiltered` block when a `trimmed.includes(\" | \")` line is found in the preamble (line 1183). This ensures the 0.18 cap only applies when both conditions from the plan hold.\n\nThe cross-iteration constraints are respected: the `-0.05` rawScore floor from iteration 8 is untouched, the layered bonus system from iterations 24/26/27 is intact, and the cap applies after all positional bonuses (lines 1233–1239).\n\n---\n\n## Change F — Trailing page reference stripping\n\n**Verdict: CORRECT regex, correct call site placement.**\n\nPlan regex: `text.replace(/\\s*\\((?:p\\.?\\s*)?\\d{1,4}\\)\\s*$/, \"\").trim()`\n\nImplementation at lines 556–558:\n```typescript\nfunction stripTrailingPageRef(text: string): string {\n  return text.replace(/\\s*\\((?:p\\.?\\s*)?\\d{1,4}\\)\\s*$/, \"\").trim();\n}\n```\n\nThe regex is identical to the plan. The function is applied in `buildCandidates` at line 681 in the pipeline `stripParentheticalGloss(stripTrailingPageRef(stripPageNumber(line.text)))` — this matches the plan's instruction to \"apply in `buildCandidates` alongside `stripPageNumber` and `stripParentheticalGloss`.\"\n\n---\n\n## Pattern 6 — \"Not fixable\" constraint\n\n**Verdict: Respected. No fix attempted.**\n\nNo code changes target the Mushroom Risotto case (title absent from document). The structural problem is untouched, consistent with the plan's explicit exclusion.\n\n---\n\n## Changes Beyond the Improvement Plan\n\n**One area goes modestly beyond the plan.**\n\nAt line 681, the call chain is:\n```typescript\nrepairOcrText(stripParentheticalGloss(stripTrailingPageRef(stripPageNumber(line.text))))\n```\n\nThe plan said to apply `stripTrailingPageRef` \"alongside `stripPageNumber` and `stripParentheticalGloss`\" but did not specify the exact order. The implementation places it between `stripPageNumber` and `stripParentheticalGloss`, which is reasonable: strip the leading page number first, then strip a trailing `(N)` ref, then strip a trailing parenthetical gloss. The ordering does not create edge-case conflicts because the patterns are disjoint: `stripPageNumber` matches leading digits, `stripTrailingPageRef` matches trailing `(N)` with optional `p.`, and `stripParentheticalGloss` matches trailing `(mixed-case text)`.\n\nNo other changes outside the plan were detected.\n\n---\n\n## Cross-Iteration Constraints\n\nAll three cross-iteration constraints mentioned in the plan are respected:\n\n1. The `-0.05` rawScore floor from iteration 8 — not touched (the floor is enforced in threshold logic, which was not modified).\n2. The `maxPositionalBoost` cap from iterations 26/27 — preserved, only the conditional value was changed.\n3. Change D normalization using the same logic as `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` — the same `[a-zà-ż]` lookaround pattern is used in both.\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\n| Change | Status | Notes |\n|--------|--------|-------|\n| A: Mixed-case OCR repair | Correct | Exact match to plan |\n| B: Garbled multi-word | Deviation (+`length <= 7` cap) | Well-justified; reduces false positives |\n| C: Polish verbs | Correct | All plan verbs present with diacritic-tolerant forms |\n| D: OCR norm for instruction | Simplified (good) with one narrow guard | Lowercase-only guard misses ALL_CAPS `4` case, but irrelevant in practice |\n| E: Positional bonus cap | Correct | Exact match to plan |\n| F: Trailing page ref | Correct | Regex and call site match plan exactly |\n| Pattern 6 | Not touched | Correctly excluded per plan |\n\nThe implementation is sound. The only item worth a follow-up note in the iteration docs is the `length <= 7` cap in Change B — document the reasoning (OCR dropped-space artifacts like `\"withGarlic\"`) so future iterations don't remove it without understanding why."}],"totalDurationMs":101465,"totalTokens":47090,"totalToolUseCount":10,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":186,"cache_read_input_tokens":43722,"output_tokens":3181,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":186},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
