{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Ai1nTajqSDN4nP3EWvSEVf","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have everything I need for a comprehensive analysis. Let me write the review.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: Performance & Scalability — `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n\n## Review Metrics\n- **Files Reviewed**: 1\n- **Critical Issues**: 0\n- **High Priority**: 2\n- **Medium Priority**: 3\n- **Low Priority / Opportunities**: 2\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThe changes introduce a measurable but bounded increase in per-candidate regex work. No individual change is catastrophically expensive. The realistic performance concern is the compounding of several medium-cost operations across the candidate loop: on a 200-line document the candidate loop runs `~400` passes through `passesHardFilters` (single + 2-join + 3-join per line) and up to `~1200` individual regex operations. None of the new regex patterns risk catastrophic backtracking. The dominant cost remains embedding inference (up to 25 `embed()` calls per document), not the regex work. However two specific code paths have design-level inefficiencies that are worth fixing.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority\n\n### 1. `passesCorroboration` is called on a hot path with an O(candidates × lines) inner scan\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1395–1406` and `:1600–1602`\n\n**Root Cause**: `passesCorroboration` at line 243 contains a nested loop: for each content word in the candidate text, it iterates over all `allLines`. The outer `filter()` calls at lines 1398 and 1601 each invoke this over every ALL_CAPS candidate. In the worst case:\n\n- `allCapsInScored` has ~10 candidates\n- Each candidate has ~5 content words\n- `allLines` has 200 lines\n\nThat is 10 × 5 × 200 = 10,000 string `.includes()` comparisons, called twice (lines 1398 and 1601), for 20,000 total. Each `.includes()` on a short uppercase string is fast in practice (~1µs in V8/Hermes), so this is about 20ms. Not catastrophic, but it also builds a new uppercase string for every comparison (`allLines[i].toUpperCase()`). The uppercase conversion is the real waste: 200 × 10 = 2,000 `toUpperCase()` calls inside the innermost loop.\n\n**Solution**: Precompute `upperLines` once before both `passesCorroboration` call sites, and accept it as a parameter (or close over a module-scoped variable during one extraction run). The function signature is internal, so this is a safe refactor:\n\n```typescript\n// In extractTitleWithEmbeddings, after splitting lines:\nconst upperLines = lines.map(l => l.toUpperCase());\n\n// Pass to passesCorroboration instead of computing inside:\nfunction passesCorroboration(\n  text: string,\n  position: number,\n  upperLines: Array<string>,  // pre-uppercased\n  startLine: number = 0\n): boolean {\n  const contentWords = extractContentWords(text); // already returns UPPERCASE\n  if (contentWords.length === 0) return true;\n\n  let corroboratedCount = 0;\n  for (const word of contentWords) {\n    for (let i = startLine; i < upperLines.length; i++) {\n      if (i === position) continue;\n      if (upperLines[i].includes(word)) {\n        corroboratedCount++;\n        break;\n      }\n    }\n  }\n  // ...\n}\n```\n\nThis eliminates ~2,000 `toUpperCase()` calls without changing behaviour.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `passesHardFilters` is called ~3× per merged line, and its inner work has grown\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:401–450` and `buildCandidates` loop at lines 682–744\n\n**Root Cause**: For each `mergedLine`, `passesHardFilters` is called up to three times: once on the single candidate (line 682), once for the 2-line join (line 725), and once for the 3-line join (line 739). On a 100-line document with 80 non-empty merged lines, that is 240 calls. Each call now includes:\n\n- `isLikelyGarbled` — itself calls `split`, two regex `.test()`, two `match()`, and a second `split` with a `some()` loop containing two more `.test()` calls. For a multi-word candidate this is ~8 regex operations.\n- `looksLikeCookingInstruction` — now potentially called twice (original + ocrNormForInstruction) when the OCR norm produces a different string. Each call tests two large regexes (`COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` with ~60 alternations, `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` with ~50).\n- `METADATA_PATTERNS.some()` — 18 regex patterns.\n- `isSectionLabel` — `stripDiacritics` (normalize + replace), two Set lookups, one `replace`.\n\nThe total cost per call is roughly 30–40 regex operations. At 240 calls: ~9,000 regex ops just for `passesHardFilters`. On Hermes (which lacks JIT for regex), this is meaningful.\n\nThe new OCR normalization for cooking-instruction detection at lines 411–415 adds two lookbehind replacements and a conditional second instruction check. The lookbehind `(?<=[a-zà-ż])4` is well-formed and not backtracking-prone, but it uses a Unicode range in a lookbehind which Hermes supports only as of recent RN versions. Verify your minimum RN target.\n\nThe `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` regex has ~50 alternations. This is not backtracking-dangerous (all alternations are literal prefixes anchored at `^`), but it will be tested O(240) times. At 50 alternations, the engine exits early on the first match, so average cost is low when most candidates are not instructions. Acceptable.\n\n**Solution**: Extract a fast pre-check that short-circuits before the expensive checks for obviously invalid candidates, and avoid repeated work on the join variants by pre-filtering `line.text` before constructing joins:\n\n```typescript\n// Before the 2-line and 3-line join construction, bail out early if line.text\n// is itself an instruction or ingredient — joins will also fail, so skip them:\nconst linePassesFast = passesHardFilters(singleText);\nif (!linePassesFast) {\n  // Still build joins in case line + next together pass, but\n  // skip the single candidate (already handled) and avoid re-running\n  // the full filter on join variants if the first line is a section label:\n  if (isAlwaysBlockJoinLabel(line.text)) continue; // joins are also blocked\n}\n```\n\nMore impactfully, memoize `passesHardFilters` on normalized text. The `seen` Set already deduplicates by lowercased text, but `passesHardFilters` is called before the dedup check. A small `Map<string, boolean>` keyed on normalized text would eliminate the repeated work on join variants that share a prefix:\n\n```typescript\nconst hardFilterCache = new Map<string, boolean>();\nfunction cachedPassesHardFilters(text: string): boolean {\n  const key = text.toLowerCase();\n  if (hardFilterCache.has(key)) return hardFilterCache.get(key)!;\n  const result = passesHardFilters(text);\n  hardFilterCache.set(key, result);\n  return result;\n}\n```\n\nReset the cache at the start of each `buildCandidates` call. Cache size will be at most a few hundred entries (bounded by document line count), well within mobile memory constraints.\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority\n\n### 3. `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` runs 12 chained `.replace()` calls per token\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:878–900`\n\n**Root Cause**: The function runs 12 sequential `.replace()` calls, many using lookbehind with `[a-zà-ż]` or `[A-ZÀ-Ż]`. Each call creates a new string. For a 6-word title this is 12 calls × 6 tokens = 72 string allocations inside `applyBlindOcrRepairMixedCase`. Since this is called from `generateBlindOcrVariants` which is only triggered for early-position candidates with OCR artifacts (line 695's `line.index <= 5` guard), the effective invocation count is very low: at most 5 lines × 2 variants each = 10 calls. That is 120 string allocations total — negligible.\n\nThe Unicode lookbehinds (`(?<=[a-zà-ż])`) are safe from catastrophic backtracking because they are fixed-length. Both Hermes (RN 0.73+) and JSC support fixed-length lookbehinds. Verify RN version if you support < 0.73.\n\n**Assessment**: No action required for the 10-second budget, but consolidating pairs like `(?<=[a-zà-ż])0` and `0(?=[a-zà-ż])` into a single regex would be cleaner:\n\n```typescript\n// Replace two calls:\n//   .replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])0/g, \"o\")\n//   .replace(/0(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, \"o\")\n// With one call (matches 0 adjacent to lowercase on either side):\n  .replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])0|0(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, \"o\")\n```\n\nThis halves the chain to 6 replacements with no semantic change.\n\n---\n\n### 4. `hasErraticCasing` is called in three distinct contexts, two of which may overlap\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:695, 697, 945, 1009`\n\n**Root Cause**: In `buildCandidates` (line 695), `hasErraticCasing(line.text)` is called once as a guard, and then if true, `hasErraticCasing(repairable)` is called again at line 697 to decide whether to normalize. When `repairable === singleText` (which is the common case — `repairOcrText` changes it only if OCR artifacts are present), these two calls are on the same string. In `normalizeErraticCasing` (line 945), `hasErraticCasing` is called once per token inside a split/map. In `normalizeOcrTitle` (line 1009), it is called on the full output string again.\n\nThe function itself is cheap: one `split`, one `isAllCaps` check, and two `match()` calls per word. For a 5-word title, that's 10 `match()` calls. Not expensive. But the call at line 697 is redundant when `line.text` has no OCR artifacts: `repairable` is set to `singleText` (result of `repairOcrText` which returns unchanged text if no artifacts), and the `hasErraticCasing` check at line 695 already ran on `line.text`. The only case where 697 differs from 695 is when `repairOcrText` changed the casing — which it does not (it only replaces digits). So the line 697 call is always redundant: if `line.text` had erratic casing, `singleText` has the same casing (digits don't affect casing). The guard at 695 is sufficient.\n\n**Solution**:\n\n```typescript\n// line 695 guard already covers the condition; line 697 re-check is redundant\nif (line.index <= 5 && (OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN.test(line.text) || hasErraticCasing(line.text))) {\n  let repairable = singleText;\n  // hasErraticCasing(repairable) === hasErraticCasing(line.text) — already known true from guard\n  if (hasErraticCasing(line.text)) {  // use cached result or inline the guard's value\n    repairable = normalizeErraticCasing(repairable);\n    // ...\n  }\n}\n```\n\nOr restructure so the boolean is captured:\n\n```typescript\nconst lineHasOcrArtifact = OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN.test(line.text);\nconst lineHasErraticCasing = hasErraticCasing(line.text);\nif (line.index <= 5 && (lineHasOcrArtifact || lineHasErraticCasing)) {\n  let repairable = singleText;\n  if (lineHasErraticCasing) {  // no re-call needed\n    repairable = normalizeErraticCasing(repairable);\n    // ...\n  }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 5. `stripTrailingPageRef` added to every candidate line in `buildCandidates`\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:681`\n\nThe call is `repairOcrText(stripParentheticalGloss(stripTrailingPageRef(stripPageNumber(line.text))))`. This adds one regex replace (`/\\s*\\((?:p\\.?\\s*)?\\d{1,4}\\)\\s*$/`) to every line. On 80 merged lines, that is 80 additional regex executions. The pattern is lightweight (anchored at `$`, no backtracking risk — the optional group `(?:p\\.?\\s*)?` is bounded). Cost is negligible: estimated < 1ms total. No action required.\n\n---\n\n## LOW Priority / Opportunities\n\n### 6. `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` — regex has ~50 alternations but is anchored, so no backtracking risk\n\nThe pattern uses `^(alt1|alt2|...)\\\\b`. Because it is anchored at `^`, the engine checks the first character of the string before entering the alternation group. If the first character does not match any alternation prefix, the whole regex fails immediately. In the common case (most candidates are not Polish cooking instructions), this is very cheap. The `\\b` word boundary at the end is also safe. No changes needed.\n\n### 7. `generateBlindOcrVariants` generates at most 2 variants for at most 5 early lines\n\nThe `line.index <= 5` guard at line 695 tightly bounds the blast radius. Even if all 5 early lines trigger variant generation, you get at most 10 additional `passesHardFilters` calls. Each variant also goes through `applyBlindOcrRepair` (12 `.replace()` calls) and `applyBlindOcrRepairMixedCase` (same). Total: ~24 additional regex chains of 12 each = 288 operations, plus 10 `passesHardFilters` calls at ~35 ops each = 350 more. Approximately 640 additional operations versus before. At ~0.5µs each on Hermes: ~0.3ms. This is well within budget.\n\n---\n\n## Overall Budget Assessment\n\n| Phase | Estimated time | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| `buildCandidates` (line processing) | 5–15ms | 240 `passesHardFilters` calls, each ~35 regex ops. Hermes no-JIT, ~0.5µs/op. |\n| `passesCorroboration` (2 calls) | 2–20ms | Bounded by ALL_CAPS candidate count; `toUpperCase` in inner loop is the main waste |\n| `embed()` × 25 candidates | 3–8s | Dominates. This is the 10-second bottleneck, not the regex work |\n| `normalizeOcrTitle` × 3 selected | < 1ms | Negligible |\n| Everything else (hasErraticCasing, generateBlindOcrVariants, stripTrailingPageRef) | < 5ms | Bounded by small constant multipliers |\n\nThe regex work introduced by all six changes combined costs under 30ms on a 200-line document on Hermes. The 10-second constraint is set entirely by the `embed()` call count. If extraction is timing out, the fix is to reduce the candidate cap (currently 25) rather than optimizing regex chains.\n\nThe two HIGH priority items (precomputing `upperLines` for corroboration, and memoizing `passesHardFilters` in the join loop) are worth fixing for code hygiene and consistency, not because they are causing timeouts today. They become important if the document size or candidate cap grows."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: aec5b41b5b1bfb21d (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 49395\ntool_uses: 15\nduration_ms: 147031</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f3952b68-8982-4bda-aefc-f210110437d7","uuid":"99faf845-04a6-4d41-84c8-1c7c312994cd","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Review performance implications of the changes in lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts. This code runs on a mobile device (React Native / Expo) — total title extraction must complete under 10 seconds.\n\nKey changes to assess:\n\n1. **`applyBlindOcrRepairToken`** (line ~878): Now runs 12 regex replacements per token (up from 4). Each uses lookbehind/lookahead with Unicode character classes like `[a-zà-ż]` and `[A-ZÀ-Ż]`. These are called per-word in `applyBlindOcrRepairMixedCase`.\n\n2. **`generateBlindOcrVariants`** (line ~958): Generates up to 2 variants (i-variant + l-variant) per candidate in the first 5 positions. Each variant runs through the full OCR repair pipeline.\n\n3. **`hasErraticCasing`** (line ~930): Called multiple times — in `buildCandidates` for early-position candidates AND in `normalizeOcrTitle`. Splits text on whitespace, then runs 2 regex matches per word.\n\n4. **`isLikelyGarbled`** multi-word check (line ~340): New `.some()` loop over words with regex test per word. Called for every candidate.\n\n5. **`passesHardFilters`** OCR normalization (line ~407): Creates `ocrNormForInstruction` via 2 regex replacements, then potentially calls `looksLikeCookingInstruction` twice (once on original, once on normalized).\n\n6. **The `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` regex** (line ~362): Now has ~50 alternations. Called for every candidate.\n\n7. **`buildCandidates`** (line ~678): Now applies `stripTrailingPageRef` (an additional regex) to every candidate line.\n\nConsider:\n- How many candidates typically exist? (up to 25 after prioritization)\n- How many lines in a typical OCR document? (50-200)\n- Regex with Unicode lookbehinds — are they expensive on Hermes/JSC?\n- Are there any O(n²) or worse patterns?\n- Could any of these regex create catastrophic backtracking?\n\nRead the file at /Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts to assess the actual code.","agentId":"aec5b41b5b1bfb21d","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have everything I need for a comprehensive analysis. Let me write the review.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: Performance & Scalability — `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n\n## Review Metrics\n- **Files Reviewed**: 1\n- **Critical Issues**: 0\n- **High Priority**: 2\n- **Medium Priority**: 3\n- **Low Priority / Opportunities**: 2\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThe changes introduce a measurable but bounded increase in per-candidate regex work. No individual change is catastrophically expensive. The realistic performance concern is the compounding of several medium-cost operations across the candidate loop: on a 200-line document the candidate loop runs `~400` passes through `passesHardFilters` (single + 2-join + 3-join per line) and up to `~1200` individual regex operations. None of the new regex patterns risk catastrophic backtracking. The dominant cost remains embedding inference (up to 25 `embed()` calls per document), not the regex work. However two specific code paths have design-level inefficiencies that are worth fixing.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority\n\n### 1. `passesCorroboration` is called on a hot path with an O(candidates × lines) inner scan\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1395–1406` and `:1600–1602`\n\n**Root Cause**: `passesCorroboration` at line 243 contains a nested loop: for each content word in the candidate text, it iterates over all `allLines`. The outer `filter()` calls at lines 1398 and 1601 each invoke this over every ALL_CAPS candidate. In the worst case:\n\n- `allCapsInScored` has ~10 candidates\n- Each candidate has ~5 content words\n- `allLines` has 200 lines\n\nThat is 10 × 5 × 200 = 10,000 string `.includes()` comparisons, called twice (lines 1398 and 1601), for 20,000 total. Each `.includes()` on a short uppercase string is fast in practice (~1µs in V8/Hermes), so this is about 20ms. Not catastrophic, but it also builds a new uppercase string for every comparison (`allLines[i].toUpperCase()`). The uppercase conversion is the real waste: 200 × 10 = 2,000 `toUpperCase()` calls inside the innermost loop.\n\n**Solution**: Precompute `upperLines` once before both `passesCorroboration` call sites, and accept it as a parameter (or close over a module-scoped variable during one extraction run). The function signature is internal, so this is a safe refactor:\n\n```typescript\n// In extractTitleWithEmbeddings, after splitting lines:\nconst upperLines = lines.map(l => l.toUpperCase());\n\n// Pass to passesCorroboration instead of computing inside:\nfunction passesCorroboration(\n  text: string,\n  position: number,\n  upperLines: Array<string>,  // pre-uppercased\n  startLine: number = 0\n): boolean {\n  const contentWords = extractContentWords(text); // already returns UPPERCASE\n  if (contentWords.length === 0) return true;\n\n  let corroboratedCount = 0;\n  for (const word of contentWords) {\n    for (let i = startLine; i < upperLines.length; i++) {\n      if (i === position) continue;\n      if (upperLines[i].includes(word)) {\n        corroboratedCount++;\n        break;\n      }\n    }\n  }\n  // ...\n}\n```\n\nThis eliminates ~2,000 `toUpperCase()` calls without changing behaviour.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `passesHardFilters` is called ~3× per merged line, and its inner work has grown\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:401–450` and `buildCandidates` loop at lines 682–744\n\n**Root Cause**: For each `mergedLine`, `passesHardFilters` is called up to three times: once on the single candidate (line 682), once for the 2-line join (line 725), and once for the 3-line join (line 739). On a 100-line document with 80 non-empty merged lines, that is 240 calls. Each call now includes:\n\n- `isLikelyGarbled` — itself calls `split`, two regex `.test()`, two `match()`, and a second `split` with a `some()` loop containing two more `.test()` calls. For a multi-word candidate this is ~8 regex operations.\n- `looksLikeCookingInstruction` — now potentially called twice (original + ocrNormForInstruction) when the OCR norm produces a different string. Each call tests two large regexes (`COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` with ~60 alternations, `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` with ~50).\n- `METADATA_PATTERNS.some()` — 18 regex patterns.\n- `isSectionLabel` — `stripDiacritics` (normalize + replace), two Set lookups, one `replace`.\n\nThe total cost per call is roughly 30–40 regex operations. At 240 calls: ~9,000 regex ops just for `passesHardFilters`. On Hermes (which lacks JIT for regex), this is meaningful.\n\nThe new OCR normalization for cooking-instruction detection at lines 411–415 adds two lookbehind replacements and a conditional second instruction check. The lookbehind `(?<=[a-zà-ż])4` is well-formed and not backtracking-prone, but it uses a Unicode range in a lookbehind which Hermes supports only as of recent RN versions. Verify your minimum RN target.\n\nThe `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` regex has ~50 alternations. This is not backtracking-dangerous (all alternations are literal prefixes anchored at `^`), but it will be tested O(240) times. At 50 alternations, the engine exits early on the first match, so average cost is low when most candidates are not instructions. Acceptable.\n\n**Solution**: Extract a fast pre-check that short-circuits before the expensive checks for obviously invalid candidates, and avoid repeated work on the join variants by pre-filtering `line.text` before constructing joins:\n\n```typescript\n// Before the 2-line and 3-line join construction, bail out early if line.text\n// is itself an instruction or ingredient — joins will also fail, so skip them:\nconst linePassesFast = passesHardFilters(singleText);\nif (!linePassesFast) {\n  // Still build joins in case line + next together pass, but\n  // skip the single candidate (already handled) and avoid re-running\n  // the full filter on join variants if the first line is a section label:\n  if (isAlwaysBlockJoinLabel(line.text)) continue; // joins are also blocked\n}\n```\n\nMore impactfully, memoize `passesHardFilters` on normalized text. The `seen` Set already deduplicates by lowercased text, but `passesHardFilters` is called before the dedup check. A small `Map<string, boolean>` keyed on normalized text would eliminate the repeated work on join variants that share a prefix:\n\n```typescript\nconst hardFilterCache = new Map<string, boolean>();\nfunction cachedPassesHardFilters(text: string): boolean {\n  const key = text.toLowerCase();\n  if (hardFilterCache.has(key)) return hardFilterCache.get(key)!;\n  const result = passesHardFilters(text);\n  hardFilterCache.set(key, result);\n  return result;\n}\n```\n\nReset the cache at the start of each `buildCandidates` call. Cache size will be at most a few hundred entries (bounded by document line count), well within mobile memory constraints.\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority\n\n### 3. `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` runs 12 chained `.replace()` calls per token\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:878–900`\n\n**Root Cause**: The function runs 12 sequential `.replace()` calls, many using lookbehind with `[a-zà-ż]` or `[A-ZÀ-Ż]`. Each call creates a new string. For a 6-word title this is 12 calls × 6 tokens = 72 string allocations inside `applyBlindOcrRepairMixedCase`. Since this is called from `generateBlindOcrVariants` which is only triggered for early-position candidates with OCR artifacts (line 695's `line.index <= 5` guard), the effective invocation count is very low: at most 5 lines × 2 variants each = 10 calls. That is 120 string allocations total — negligible.\n\nThe Unicode lookbehinds (`(?<=[a-zà-ż])`) are safe from catastrophic backtracking because they are fixed-length. Both Hermes (RN 0.73+) and JSC support fixed-length lookbehinds. Verify RN version if you support < 0.73.\n\n**Assessment**: No action required for the 10-second budget, but consolidating pairs like `(?<=[a-zà-ż])0` and `0(?=[a-zà-ż])` into a single regex would be cleaner:\n\n```typescript\n// Replace two calls:\n//   .replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])0/g, \"o\")\n//   .replace(/0(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, \"o\")\n// With one call (matches 0 adjacent to lowercase on either side):\n  .replace(/(?<=[a-zà-ż])0|0(?=[a-zà-ż])/g, \"o\")\n```\n\nThis halves the chain to 6 replacements with no semantic change.\n\n---\n\n### 4. `hasErraticCasing` is called in three distinct contexts, two of which may overlap\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:695, 697, 945, 1009`\n\n**Root Cause**: In `buildCandidates` (line 695), `hasErraticCasing(line.text)` is called once as a guard, and then if true, `hasErraticCasing(repairable)` is called again at line 697 to decide whether to normalize. When `repairable === singleText` (which is the common case — `repairOcrText` changes it only if OCR artifacts are present), these two calls are on the same string. In `normalizeErraticCasing` (line 945), `hasErraticCasing` is called once per token inside a split/map. In `normalizeOcrTitle` (line 1009), it is called on the full output string again.\n\nThe function itself is cheap: one `split`, one `isAllCaps` check, and two `match()` calls per word. For a 5-word title, that's 10 `match()` calls. Not expensive. But the call at line 697 is redundant when `line.text` has no OCR artifacts: `repairable` is set to `singleText` (result of `repairOcrText` which returns unchanged text if no artifacts), and the `hasErraticCasing` check at line 695 already ran on `line.text`. The only case where 697 differs from 695 is when `repairOcrText` changed the casing — which it does not (it only replaces digits). So the line 697 call is always redundant: if `line.text` had erratic casing, `singleText` has the same casing (digits don't affect casing). The guard at 695 is sufficient.\n\n**Solution**:\n\n```typescript\n// line 695 guard already covers the condition; line 697 re-check is redundant\nif (line.index <= 5 && (OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN.test(line.text) || hasErraticCasing(line.text))) {\n  let repairable = singleText;\n  // hasErraticCasing(repairable) === hasErraticCasing(line.text) — already known true from guard\n  if (hasErraticCasing(line.text)) {  // use cached result or inline the guard's value\n    repairable = normalizeErraticCasing(repairable);\n    // ...\n  }\n}\n```\n\nOr restructure so the boolean is captured:\n\n```typescript\nconst lineHasOcrArtifact = OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN.test(line.text);\nconst lineHasErraticCasing = hasErraticCasing(line.text);\nif (line.index <= 5 && (lineHasOcrArtifact || lineHasErraticCasing)) {\n  let repairable = singleText;\n  if (lineHasErraticCasing) {  // no re-call needed\n    repairable = normalizeErraticCasing(repairable);\n    // ...\n  }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 5. `stripTrailingPageRef` added to every candidate line in `buildCandidates`\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:681`\n\nThe call is `repairOcrText(stripParentheticalGloss(stripTrailingPageRef(stripPageNumber(line.text))))`. This adds one regex replace (`/\\s*\\((?:p\\.?\\s*)?\\d{1,4}\\)\\s*$/`) to every line. On 80 merged lines, that is 80 additional regex executions. The pattern is lightweight (anchored at `$`, no backtracking risk — the optional group `(?:p\\.?\\s*)?` is bounded). Cost is negligible: estimated < 1ms total. No action required.\n\n---\n\n## LOW Priority / Opportunities\n\n### 6. `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` — regex has ~50 alternations but is anchored, so no backtracking risk\n\nThe pattern uses `^(alt1|alt2|...)\\\\b`. Because it is anchored at `^`, the engine checks the first character of the string before entering the alternation group. If the first character does not match any alternation prefix, the whole regex fails immediately. In the common case (most candidates are not Polish cooking instructions), this is very cheap. The `\\b` word boundary at the end is also safe. No changes needed.\n\n### 7. `generateBlindOcrVariants` generates at most 2 variants for at most 5 early lines\n\nThe `line.index <= 5` guard at line 695 tightly bounds the blast radius. Even if all 5 early lines trigger variant generation, you get at most 10 additional `passesHardFilters` calls. Each variant also goes through `applyBlindOcrRepair` (12 `.replace()` calls) and `applyBlindOcrRepairMixedCase` (same). Total: ~24 additional regex chains of 12 each = 288 operations, plus 10 `passesHardFilters` calls at ~35 ops each = 350 more. Approximately 640 additional operations versus before. At ~0.5µs each on Hermes: ~0.3ms. This is well within budget.\n\n---\n\n## Overall Budget Assessment\n\n| Phase | Estimated time | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| `buildCandidates` (line processing) | 5–15ms | 240 `passesHardFilters` calls, each ~35 regex ops. Hermes no-JIT, ~0.5µs/op. |\n| `passesCorroboration` (2 calls) | 2–20ms | Bounded by ALL_CAPS candidate count; `toUpperCase` in inner loop is the main waste |\n| `embed()` × 25 candidates | 3–8s | Dominates. This is the 10-second bottleneck, not the regex work |\n| `normalizeOcrTitle` × 3 selected | < 1ms | Negligible |\n| Everything else (hasErraticCasing, generateBlindOcrVariants, stripTrailingPageRef) | < 5ms | Bounded by small constant multipliers |\n\nThe regex work introduced by all six changes combined costs under 30ms on a 200-line document on Hermes. The 10-second constraint is set entirely by the `embed()` call count. If extraction is timing out, the fix is to reduce the candidate cap (currently 25) rather than optimizing regex chains.\n\nThe two HIGH priority items (precomputing `upperLines` for corroboration, and memoizing `passesHardFilters` in the join loop) are worth fixing for code hygiene and consistency, not because they are causing timeouts today. They become important if the document size or candidate cap grows."}],"totalDurationMs":147031,"totalTokens":49395,"totalToolUseCount":15,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":492,"cache_read_input_tokens":44774,"output_tokens":4128,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":492},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
