{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_015MRCE46Z45zBxR54V5o2oQ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me check two concerns:\n\n1. The `hasErraticCasing` change from `< 3` to `< 5` - this means words of length 3 and 4 will no longer be detected as erratically cased. Is there a test case that depends on this? The function is used in `normalizeErraticCasing` (which feeds into `buildCandidates` and `normalizeOcrTitle`). A 4-char erratically cased word like \"KoPy\" in \"KoPyTka\" would... wait, \"KoPyTka\" is 7 chars, so it would still be caught. Let me think about what 3-4 char words could legitimately have erratic casing... Words like \"McD\" (3 chars) would be exempted by isAllCaps check. \n\nFor a 4-char word like \"ZAPa\" to trigger erratic casing, you'd need the inner portion to have at least 2 uppercase letters, which the old threshold would catch. But raising it to 5 means we'd miss these shorter OCR artifacts, which is probably the safer trade-off since short words are more prone to scanning errors anyway.\n\nThe tests all passed, so the change seems fine. Now I'm checking that the ALL_CAPS repairs in `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` match what's in `applyBlindOcrRepair` — the character mappings like `¡→I`, `€→E`, and `[ÍÌ]→I` are all there and consistent.\n\nI'm tracing through the control flow to make sure the repairs apply correctly: when `applyBlindOcrRepair` processes text, it either applies the full ALL_CAPS repairs if the whole text is capitalized, or it delegates to `applyBlindOcrRepairMixedCase` which processes each token individually, and those tokens get their own ALL_CAPS repairs if they happen to be all caps.\n\nNow I'm comparing the actual repair rules between the full-text and token-level paths to check if they're truly equivalent—the full-text version uses lookahead and lookbehind for some replacements while the token-level might handle them differently. I'm noticing the token-level ALL_CAPS replacements are now matching the mixed-case versions, which is good. But I'm questioning whether I should add the accented character mappings like `[ÍÌ]→I` to the mixed-case branch too, since the ALL_CAPS version has them but the mixed-case doesn't.\n\nActually, looking at the full `applyBlindOcrRepair` function, it seems intentional that mixed-case text skips the `[ÍÌ]` treatment—those accented characters are probably valid in mixed-case contexts, so they shouldn't be normalized away.\n\nNow I'm concerned about a performance issue: `lineHasErraticCasing` is being computed for every line in `buildCandidates`, but it used to only be checked for early-position lines. Let me trace through the logic to see if this is actually a problem.\n\nLooking at lines 695-696, the `hasErraticCasing` check is now happening unconditionally before the `line.index <= 5` guard, which means on a 200-line document I'm doing ~195 unnecessary calls. Each call involves splitting on whitespace and running regex matches per word, so that's potentially thousands of extra regex operations. It's probably negligible in practice—maybe a millisecond or so—but it would be cleaner to move that check inside the guard where it's actually needed.\n\nActually, looking at the next version, I see the fix: moving `hasErraticCasing` inside the `if (line.index <= 5)` block. Since it's only used there anyway, this eliminates the unnecessary calls entirely.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2340,"cache_read_input_tokens":76791,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2340},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f3952b68-8982-4bda-aefc-f210110437d7","uuid":"22084076-132c-4b10-818c-e8b4d7f9f664"}
